var _frontmatter = {
  "templateKey": "content-pages",
  "title": "How do writers compose in the digital age?",
  "key": "how-do-writers-compose-in-the-digital-age",
  "parentKey": "how-do-we-write-in-the-digital-age",
  "points": [{
    "point": "Author Naomi Silver explains how writing has changed in the digital age: VIDEO INTERVIEW",
    "title": "Author Interview"
  }, {
    "point": "Writing in the digital age is—as it has always been—about making choices: What tools are available? What will be most effective with this audience? Consider Kaitlin, a student featured in [Chapter 8](https://hdl.handle.net/2027/fulcrum.10079890/poi.13).\n\nWhen she starts her [gateway portfolio](https://hdl.handle.net/2027/fulcrum.10079890/poi.19), she builds a website that is identical in form to print, but that is distributed electronically. Author Naomi writes:\n\n:::md-component ExpandableBlockquote previewText=\"In%20appearance%2C%20Kaitlin%u2019s%20Gateway%20%20eportfolio%20%20is%20%20very%20%20similar%20%20to%20%20Madeleine%u2019s%20%20Capstone%20%20eportfolio%20%u2026\" fullText=\"%5BIn%20appearance%2C%20Kaitlin%u2019s%20Gateway%20%20eportfolio%20%20is%20%20very%20%20similar%20%20to%20%20Madeleine%u2019s%20%20Capstone%20%20eportfolio%20-%20text-only%20on%20an%20unobtrusive%20background.%20In%20a%20short%20paragraph%20on%20the%20home%20page%2C%20preceding%20the%20description%20of%20the%20artifacts%20I%20quoted%20above%2C%20she%20explains%20this%20look%2C%20writing%2C%20%u2018Welcome%20to%20my%20electronic%20writing%20portfolio%21%20%28see%20figure%208.3%29.%20Despite%20its%20format%2C%20this%20is%20not%20a%20blog.%20Rather%2C%20it%20is%20the%20paperless%2C%20online%20equivalent%20of%20a%20printed%20portfolio%20that%20gives%20you%20samples%20of%20my%20writing%20from%20my%20different%20academic%20concentrations.%u2019%20Here%20Kaitlin%20seems%20to%20be%20offering%20a%20precise%20definition%u2014and%20celebration%u2014of%20%5C%5Ba%5D%20%u2018print%20uploaded%u2019%20digital%20portfolio%2C%20%u2018a%20version%20of%20portfolio%20that%20is%20identical%20in%20form%20to%20the%20print%20but%20that%20is%20distributed%20electronically.%27%5D%28https%3A//hdl.handle.net/2027/fulcrum.10079890/poi.19%29\"\n\nKaitlin’s [capstone portfolio](https://hdl.handle.net/2027/fulcrum.10079890/poi.23) looks very different from her gateway one. She explains the visual difference and how digital tools and the capacity of the portfolio to live online influences how she thinks about what it should look like:\n\n:::md-component ExpandableBlockquote previewText=\"I%20hated%20my%20gateway%20portfolio%20..\" fullText=\"%5BI%20hated%20my%20gateway%20portfolio.%20It%20was%20just%20bland%20and%20boring.%20I%20was%20very%20nervous%20to%20put%20anything%20personal%20on%20it.%20It%20was%20not%20visual.%20It%20was%20just%20a%20bunch%20of%20text%20that%20really%20wasn%u2019t%20broken%20up%20by%20anything.%20It%20wasn%u2019t%20really%20multimedia.%20I%20mean%2C%20there%20were%20links%2C%20but%20just%20in%20the%20text%2C%20like%20here%u2019s%20a%20blue%20word%20here%20and%20there....I%20had%20this%20idea%20that%20it%20really%20needs%20to%20look%20like%20a%20resume%2C%20but%20just%20like%20a%20normal%20paper%20thing%20but%20online%20so%20you%20don%u2019t%20actually%20have%20to%20have%20paper....Whereas%2C%20with%20the%20capstone%20portfolio%2C%20I%20was%20challenging%20myself%20not%20to%20take%20%20paper%20%20and%20%20put%20%20it%20%20online%2C%20%20but%20%20something%20%20that%20%20was%20%20created%20%20online%20%20and%20%20lives%20online.%20The%20content%20was%20made%20for%20that%20form.%20I%20think%20that%20was%20the%20biggest%20difference%20in%20my%20mind.%5D%28https%3A//hdl.handle.net/2027/fulcrum.10079890/poi.20%29\"\n\nKaitlin recognizes that print and digital are different spaces that require different ways to present her material. She makes choices that attend to her audience and purpose in the digital space, and she explains her selections. Her ability to do make and explain her choices indicates that she is developing as a writer.\n\n**FOR INSTRUCTORS:** teaching multimodal writing\n\nKaitlin describes the role of considering the relationship between content and form in a way that was different from what she had learned in her other classes:\n\n:::md-component ExpandableBlockquote previewText=\"Mostly%20because%20when%20I%20start%20writing%2C%20I%20usually%20want%20to%20write%20%u2026\" fullText=\"%5BMostly%20because%20when%20I%20start%20writing%2C%20I%20usually%20want%20to%20write%20for%20pages%20and%20pages%20and%20pages.%20The%20challenge%20was%20how%20can%20I%20achieve%20the%20same%20effect%20but%20in%20a%20visual%20format%20or%20in%20a%20format%20that%20is%20something%20besides%20a%20printed%208%20x%2011%20piece%20of%20paper%3F%20%u2026%20I%20would%20start%20writing%20for%20paragraphs%2C%20like%20for%20each%20bullet%20point.%20I%20said%2C%20%u2018Okay%2C%20how%20can%20I%20figure%20out%20how%20to%20make%20it%20academic%20but%20at%20the%20same%20time%20not%20go%20on%20for%20pages%3F%u2019%5D%28https%3A//hdl.handle.net/2027/fulcrum.10079890/poi.20%29\"\n\nStudents and writers frequently compose digitally in non-academic spaces, but they need more guidance in academic spaces to develop rhetorical awareness. Strategy 3 [on this website](https://lsa.umich.edu/sweetland/instructors/teaching-resources/sequencing-and-scaffolding-assignments.html) shows ways rhetorical instruction (versus just technical instruction) on a digital platform can be taught.\n\nTo see more eportfolios, check out the screencasted eports of the following 9 students who gave permissions to share their student eportfolios. They are linked via their pseudonyms, but you’ll see their given names on their eportfolios.\n\n* [Jenna’s Gateway Eportfolio](https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.10079890.cmp.310)\n* [Shannon’s Capstone Eportfolio](https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.10079890.cmp.311)\n* [Jonah’s Gateway Eportfolio](https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.10079890.cmp.312)\n* [Jonah’s Capstone Eportfolio](https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.10079890.cmp.313)\n* [Samantha’s Capstone Eportfolio](https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.10079890.cmp.314)\n* [Samantha’s Gateway Eportfolio](https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.10079890.cmp.315)\n* [Dana’s Capstone Eportfolio](https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.10079890.cmp.316)\n* [Adrienne’s Gateway Eportfolio](https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.10079890.cmp.317)\n* [Amanda’s Gateway Eportfolio](https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.10079890.cmp.318)\n* [Julia’s Capstone Eportfolio](https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.10079890.cmp.319)\n* [Dan’s Capstone Eportfolio](https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.10079890.cmp.320)\n\nAnd here for their sitesucked (web stable) eports\n\n* [Shannon’s Capstone Eportfolio](https://doi.org/10.7302/Z2KW5D9X)\n* [Dana’s Gateway Eportfolio](https://doi.org/10.7302/Z2QN6506)\n* [Dan’s Gateway Eportfolio](https://doi.org/10.7302/Z2VD6WPP)\n* [Adrienne’s Gateway Eportfolio](https://doi.org/10.7302/Z2028PS3)\n* [Samantha’s Capstone Eportfolio](https://doi.org/10.7302/Z23T9FFM)\n* [Samantha’s Gateway Eportfolio](https://doi.org/10.7302/Z27M065W)\n* [Julia’s Capstone Eportfolio](https://doi.org/10.7302/Z2CC0XX8)\n* [Amanda’s Gateway Eportfolio](https://doi.org/10.7302/Z2H41PPF)\n* [Jenna’s Capstone Eportfolio](https://doi.org/10.7302/Z2MW2FCD)\n* [Jenna’s Gateway Eportfolio](https://doi.org/10.7302/Z2RJ4GQV)\n* [Jonah’s Gateway Eportfolio](https://doi.org/10.7302/Z2W957D4)\n\n",
    "title": "Case Study"
  }, {
    "point": "When writers are able to make choices in what they say and how they say it, they start to see themselves as developing writers. In Chapter 8, Silver explains:\n\n:::md-component ExpandableBlockquote previewText=\"In%20brief%2C%20in%20this%20analysis%2C%20writerly%20self-identity%20is%20found%20to%20comprise%20a%20new%20factor%20%u2026\" fullText=\"%5BIn%20brief%2C%20in%20this%20analysis%2C%20writerly%20self-identity%20is%20found%20to%20comprise%20a%20new%20factor%20in%20how%20multimodal%20writing%20development%20becomes%20observable%2C%20such%20that%20the%20most%20robust%20development%20is%20characterized%20not%20only%20by%20a%20composer%u2019s%20expanded%20conception%20of%20writing%2C%20but%20also%20their%20expanded%20self-perception%20as%20a%20writer.%20In%20this%20broader%20frame%2C%20writers%20view%20substance%20and%20style%20as%20integrally%20linked%2C%20and%20also%20view%20themselves%20as%20composers%20in%20any%20mode%20or%20medium%20that%20enables%20them%20best%20to%20enact%20an%20argument%20within%20a%20given%20rhetorical%20situation.%20However%2C%20an%20additional%20finding%20is%20that%20development%20via%20reflection%20during%20eportfolio%20construction%20does%20not%20necessarily%20lead%20to%20development%20%20in%20multimodal%20composition%u2014the%20two%20seem%20to%20proceed%20independently.%5D%28https%3A//hdl.handle.net/2027/fulcrum.10079890/poi.20%29\"\n\nOne caveat: even if students could talk about their choices, they weren’t necessarily reflected in their portfolios and vice versa. Development is uneven.\n\n**VIDEO INTERVIEW:** Author Naomi Silver explains the relationship.",
    "title": "Writing multimodally and becoming “a writer”"
  }],
  "afterPoints": "Writing in the digital age uses all available means—text, image, video, sound, and digital tools—to communicate more effectively and purposefully than “words on a page” alone. The thoughtful selection of multimodal elements can enhance the effectiveness of a message to an audience"
};

